{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-project-jsx","path":"/projects/mapping-the-internet-part-two/","result":{"data":{"post":{"html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/7db30/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 91.49999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/ba381/the-start-of-interdependent-links.webp 200w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/7f61c/the-start-of-interdependent-links.webp 400w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/d00b9/the-start-of-interdependent-links.webp 800w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/92f8c/the-start-of-interdependent-links.webp 1200w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/05359/the-start-of-interdependent-links.webp 1494w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/webp\"\n        />\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/772e8/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png 200w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/e17e5/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png 400w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/5a190/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png 800w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/c1b63/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png 1200w,\n/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/7db30/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png 1494w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/png\"\n        />\n        <img\n          class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n          src=\"/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/5a190/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png\"\n          alt=\"Starting the links\"\n          title=\"Starting the links\"\n          loading=\"lazy\"\n          style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        />\n      </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Did reading the previous instalment of \"mapping the internet\" <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"../backlink-crawler/\" title=\"read here\">read here</a> leave you a bit... underwhelmed?</p>\n<p>Same here.\nI mean, sure I had built a little program that could follow and store links on the internet, but it couldn't be ran continuously (could not store the crawling state between runs), and there was just no easy way to traverse or visualise the graph <em>yawn</em>.</p>\n<p>So, in this chapter I am going to go through how we have improved this service to become the beautifully graphical service that is:</p>\n<p><a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph/\" title=\"jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph</a></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>NOTE: By default, the graph starts from <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://jamesjarvis.io\" title=\"jamesjarvis.io\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">jamesjarvis.io</a>, but if you want to change it to start from a page of your choosing (provided it has managed to scrape that part of the web already), you can give it a shot by changing the url query parameter such as: <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph/?url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London\" title=\"/?url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">/?url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2>Part 1: Maintaining state</h2>\n<p>So I wanted to eventually run this service on a raspberry pi 4 I currently have just sitting in my attic doing <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"../speedtest/\" title=\"occasional speedtests\">occasional speedtests</a>.</p>\n<p>I've also decided that I want to be able to stop and start the crawls (say, when performing an upgrade), without losing any data between runs.</p>\n<p>In order to facilitate this, I need to have a list of URL's that have been \"seen\" but not \"crawled\" yet.</p>\n<p>I had 3 ways I could think of doing this:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Spin up a message queue system, like <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://kafka.apache.org\" title=\"kafka\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">kafka</a> or <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://www.rabbitmq.com\" title=\"rabbitMQ\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">rabbitMQ</a> to store unprocessed URLs and yeet them out to processors for the actual crawling.</li>\n<li>Add another table in the database, with the pending URLs.</li>\n<li>Store this information in a simple queue file (read from the top, append to the bottom).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>I tried all 3:</p>\n<h3>RabbitMQ</h3>\n<p>First, I tried RabbitMQ, and got it working after a few hours of mucking about with it.</p>\n<p>However, it <em>ate</em> my poor raspberry pi's RAM as soon as the queue was over a few thousand URLs, and I couldn't work out how to persist messages properly.</p>\n<p>I also didn't really need the complexity, as I didn't want my ISP to boot me off the network for making a continuous 100 requests/s, so I wouldn't have bothered with more than one consumer anyway.</p>\n<p>If I was building this to be an actual, scaleable service, then I'd have swallowed the extra AWS bill and continued, but this ain't it chief.</p>\n<h3>Whack it in a DB table</h3>\n<p>Another embarassing thing about the infra for this project is that I'm running the raspberry pi with an 8 year old 1TB external hard drive I had lying around.</p>\n<p>It's not the fastest and is in fact the biggest performance bottleneck (if I could be bothered, I would have bought an SSD but this isn't worth £80 + dealing with this limitation is interesting enough).</p>\n<p>As a result of my cheapskate-ness, this is also out of the question, I needed something more lightweight.</p>\n<h3>Simple file based queue system</h3>\n<p>This was the way, effectively traverse the web in a breadth-first fashion by appending any found URLs to the end of a list, and crawl any URLs by taking from the top.</p>\n<p>Nice and easy.</p>\n<h2>Part 2: Making the data easy to query</h2>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/720e3/api-splashscreen.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 20.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/ba381/api-splashscreen.webp 200w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/7f61c/api-splashscreen.webp 400w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/d00b9/api-splashscreen.webp 800w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/92f8c/api-splashscreen.webp 1200w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/fad48/api-splashscreen.webp 1600w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/a2081/api-splashscreen.webp 1962w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/webp\"\n        />\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/772e8/api-splashscreen.png 200w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/e17e5/api-splashscreen.png 400w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/5a190/api-splashscreen.png 800w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/c1b63/api-splashscreen.png 1200w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/29007/api-splashscreen.png 1600w,\n/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/720e3/api-splashscreen.png 1962w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/png\"\n        />\n        <img\n          class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n          src=\"/static/46ba01d72b8b7138a57f5953d3deee5f/5a190/api-splashscreen.png\"\n          alt=\"Splashscreen for the API\"\n          title=\"Splashscreen for the API\"\n          loading=\"lazy\"\n          style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        />\n      </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Eventually, I wanted to expose this information, but in an easily cacheable and web friendly way.</p>\n<p>Enter: an API service.</p>\n<p>You can actually check it out if you want at <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://api.jamesjarvis.io\" title=\"api.jamesjarvis.io\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">api.jamesjarvis.io</a>.</p>\n<p>It's been set up to be as easily cache-able (thanks to cloudflare) as possible, and it's open for anyone to use, provided you're aware it's hitting the shitbox in my attic and I don't want my ISP to throw me off their network.</p>\n<p>Also, I used different queries than the first iteration of this project, in order to speed it up.\nIndexes help a lot as well! Once the DB grew to >100k items queries used to take minutes, and now after some enthusiastic indexing can take &#x3C;1s.</p>\n<p>Some fun things you can do with it:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Find all pages at a particular host (limited to 100): <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://api.jamesjarvis.io/pages/en.wikipedia.org\" title=\"/pages/en.wikipedia.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">/pages/en.wikipedia.org</a></li>\n<li>Get an overview of a particular page (just URL, host and links from, limited to 100): <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://api.jamesjarvis.io/page/e518da42a48097ceb7648a9961428e300f2db545\" title=\"/page/HASH\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">/page/HASH</a></li>\n<li>Find all links <em>from</em> a particular page (limited to 100): <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://api.jamesjarvis.io/linksFrom/e518da42a48097ceb7648a9961428e300f2db545\" title=\"/linksFrom/HASH\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">/linksFrom/HASH</a></li>\n<li>Find all links <em>to</em> a particular page (limited to 100): <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://api.jamesjarvis.io/linksTo/e518da42a48097ceb7648a9961428e300f2db545\" title=\"/linksTo/HASH\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">/linksTo/HASH</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The last one is currently not being used by myself, though I may make an inverse graph traversal, whereby you can discover all the pages that link to a page...</p>\n<p>I've also set up my <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"../eink-dashboard/\" title=\"e-ink display\">e-ink display</a> to monitor the number of <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://api.jamesjarvis.io/countPages\" title=\"URL's crawled\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">URL's crawled</a> and <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://api.jamesjarvis.io/countLinks\" title=\"links found\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">links found</a> for my own amusement as well.</p>\n<h3>Self hosted??</h3>\n<p>Yup, it's slow as shit and is as reliable as my ISP (who apparently work on a <em>best effort</em> case), but thanks to some aggressive cloudflare caching, the most common endpoints should be relatively quick.</p>\n<h2>Part 3: Graphical representation</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"What would a visual representation of browsing the internet look like?\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/6660b/web-graph.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75.49999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/ba381/web-graph.webp 200w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/7f61c/web-graph.webp 400w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/d00b9/web-graph.webp 800w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/92f8c/web-graph.webp 1200w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/fad48/web-graph.webp 1600w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/23995/web-graph.webp 2278w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/webp\"\n        />\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/772e8/web-graph.png 200w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/e17e5/web-graph.png 400w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/5a190/web-graph.png 800w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/c1b63/web-graph.png 1200w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/29007/web-graph.png 1600w,\n/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/6660b/web-graph.png 2278w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/png\"\n        />\n        <img\n          class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n          src=\"/static/ecaccbc632bc385893fc24565019a6ea/5a190/web-graph.png\"\n          alt=\"Look mum, I&#39;ve crashed my browser!\"\n          title=\"Look mum, I&#39;ve crashed my browser!\"\n          loading=\"lazy\"\n          style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        />\n      </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Check it out at <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph/\" title=\"jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph</a> , and if you want to start from a website of your choosing, you can modify the url query param like: <code class=\"language-text\">https://jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph/?url={your_page_here}</code>.</p>\n<p>Because I couldn't be bothered to set up a proper react application + build process for this project, the whole thing is in one html file, and actually transpiles the required javascript from reactJS source on load time - maybe not the fastest but hey this isn't exactly a performance project + it's so easy to deploy.</p>\n<p>You can check out the whole front-end source <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://github.com/jamesjarvis/web-graph/blob/master/frontend/index.html\" title=\"here\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">here</a>, ~200 lines is all you need for this <em>beauty</em>.</p>\n<p>I ended up using a react wrapper around <a class=\"siteLink\" href=\"https://d3js.org\" title=\"D3.js\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow noreferrer\">D3.js</a> for the actual graphing, and it made me remember just how much I love and hate javascript.\nIt's a rocky relationship.</p>\n<p>You'll also notice that running this site is very cpu intensive, and yes it is, nothing more to add really.\nMy personal record was <code class=\"language-text\">1874 nodes</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">3556 links</code> expanded before my browser crashed, your mileage may vary.</p>\n<h2>Part 4: What have I learnt from this?</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Hardware can be a real bottleneck, next time use an SSD for IO intensive operations.</li>\n<li>Building services to be resilient to failure is extremely liberating.</li>\n<li>JavaScript still sucks to use, package management is still hell and documentation is generally just a bit weak, considering you get zero type information from the language itself.</li>\n<li>Proper database indexes are the difference between good and shit.</li>\n<li>Caching is still amazing.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Some of my favourite snippets of code:</p>\n<h3>Channel based interface for reading off of a queue</h3>\n<p>Look how neat this is, as waiting to read from the queue channel / sending to the processing channel are both blocking operations, this works as fast as these two components.\nWe are also able to pre-fetch a number of items from the queue's file if we wanted to improve performance a bit.</p>\n<p>This also enables an easy method of gracefully shutting down the program.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"go\"><pre class=\"language-go\"><code class=\"language-go\">linkProcessor<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> err <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> linkprocessor<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">NewLinkProcessor</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>\n\tlinkStorage<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n\t<span class=\"token number\">500</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n\tqueue<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n\t<span class=\"token number\">1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n<span class=\"token function\">failOnError</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>err<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"Could not initialise link processor\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\nlog<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">\"Begin processing...\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\nurlProcessingChan <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> linkProcessor<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">SpawnWorkers</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token number\">2</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\nsigs <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> <span class=\"token function\">make</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">chan</span> os<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>Signal<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">4</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\nsignal<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Notify</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>sigs<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> syscall<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>SIGTERM<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> syscall<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>SIGINT<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> syscall<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>SIGHUP<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> syscall<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>SIGKILL<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\nticker <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> time<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">NewTicker</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token number\">10</span> <span class=\"token operator\">*</span> time<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>Minute<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">defer</span> ticker<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Stop</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\nprocessing <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">for</span> processing <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t<span class=\"token keyword\">select</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t<span class=\"token keyword\">case</span> s <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span>sigs<span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\tprocessing <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">false</span>\n\t\tlog<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Printf</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">\"Received signal %s, shutting down gracefully...\\n\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> s<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\t<span class=\"token keyword\">case</span> url <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span>queue<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">DeQueue</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\turlProcessingChan <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span> url\n\t<span class=\"token keyword\">case</span> <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span>ticker<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>C<span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\tlog<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Printf</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">\"%d urls in the queue\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> queue<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Length</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span>linkProcessor<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">GracefulShutdown</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\nlog<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">\"===== Shut down link processor =====\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<h3>Periodic batcher from a buffered channel</h3>\n<p>This is a slightly improved version from the original post.</p>\n<p>This turns out to be a great way to convert a message by message insert operation into a batchable operation.\nIt also works as a great way to rate limit database operations, as you can still fill up the channel up to the buffer size, and slowly drain it at whatever rate you choose.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"go\"><pre class=\"language-go\"><code class=\"language-go\"><span class=\"token keyword\">func</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>pb <span class=\"token operator\">*</span>PageBatcher<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token function\">Worker</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>endSignal <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"token keyword\">chan</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">bool</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> doneChan <span class=\"token keyword\">chan</span><span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span> <span class=\"token builtin\">bool</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t<span class=\"token comment\">// We want it to die on the endSignal, but otherwise keep looping</span>\n\t<span class=\"token keyword\">for</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">select</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">case</span> <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span>endSignal<span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\t\tdoneChan <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">return</span>\n\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">case</span> <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span>time<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">After</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token number\">100</span> <span class=\"token operator\">*</span> time<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>Millisecond<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">var</span> pages <span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span><span class=\"token operator\">*</span>Page\n\n\t\tRemaining<span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">for</span> i <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> <span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span> i <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;</span> pb<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>maxBatch<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span> i<span class=\"token operator\">++</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">select</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">case</span> page <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;-</span>pb<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>bufChan<span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\t\t\t\tpages <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token function\">append</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>pages<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> page<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\t\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">default</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">break</span> Remaining\n\t\t\t\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">if</span> <span class=\"token function\">len</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>pages<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token number\">0</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">break</span>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token comment\">// The batch processing</span>\n\t\t\terr <span class=\"token operator\">:=</span> pb<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>s<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">BatchAddPages</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>pages<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token keyword\">if</span> err <span class=\"token operator\">!=</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">nil</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\t\t\t\tlog<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">Printf</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">\"Batch adding pages failed!: %e\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> err<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\t\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>","excerpt":"Did reading the previous instalment of \"mapping the internet\"  leave you a bit... underwhelmed? Same here.\nI mean, sure I had built a little program that could follow and store links on the internet…","fields":{"slug":"/projects/mapping-the-internet-part-two/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"⠪ Mapping the Internet, part deux","date":"2021-02","tech":["Go","JavaScript","Postgres"],"link":"https://jamesjarvis.github.io/web-graph/","source":"https://github.com/jamesjarvis/web-graph","previewImage":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":1200,"height":1099,"src":"/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/f3583/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png","srcSet":"/static/60c4b11d0c0c7250c5e09e1be0584a09/f3583/the-start-of-interdependent-links.png 1x"}}}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/projects/mapping-the-internet-part-two/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/projects/mappyboi/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"📍 Visualising location history"}},"next":null}},"staticQueryHashes":["602281340","682078843"]}